80371 {
80372 int rc;
80373 int destMode; /* Destination journal mode */
80374 int pgszSrc = 0; /* Source page size */
80375 int pgszDest = 0; /* Destination page size */
80376
80377#ifdef SQLITE_ENABLE_API_ARMOR
80378 if( p==0 ) return SQLITE_MISUSE_BKPT;
80379#endif
80380 sqlite3_mutex_enter(p->pSrcDb->mutex);
80381 sqlite3BtreeEnter(p->pSrc);
80382 if( p->pDestDb ){
80383 sqlite3_mutex_enter(p->pDestDb->mutex);
80384 }
80385
80386 rc = p->rc;
80387 if( !isFatalError(rc) ){
80388 Pager * const pSrcPager = sqlite3BtreePager(p->pSrc); /* Source pager */
80389 Pager * const pDestPager = sqlite3BtreePager(p->pDest); /* Dest pager */
80390 int ii; /* Iterator variable */
80391 int nSrcPage = -1; /* Size of source db in pages */
80392 int bCloseTrans = 0; /* True if src db requires unlocking */
80393
80394 /* If the source pager is currently in a write-transaction, return
80395 ** SQLITE_BUSY immediately.
80396 */
80397 if( p->pDestDb && p->pSrc->pBt->inTransaction==TRANS_WRITE ){
80398 rc = SQLITE_BUSY;
80399 }else{
80400 rc = SQLITE_OK;
80401 }
80402
80403 /* If there is no open read-transaction on the source database, open
80404 ** one now. If a transaction is opened here, then it will be closed
80405 ** before this function exits.
80406 */
80407 if( rc==SQLITE_OK && SQLITE_TXN_NONE==sqlite3BtreeTxnState(p->pSrc) ){
80408 rc = sqlite3BtreeBeginTrans(p->pSrc, 0, 0);
80409 bCloseTrans = 1;
80410 }
80411
80412 /* If the destination database has not yet been locked (i.e. if this
80413 ** is the first call to backup_step() for the current backup operation),
80414 ** try to set its page size to the same as the source database. This
80415 ** is especially important on ZipVFS systems, as in that case it is
80416 ** not possible to create a database file that uses one page size by
80417 ** writing to it with another. */
80418 if( p->bDestLocked==0 && rc==SQLITE_OK && setDestPgsz(p)==SQLITE_NOMEM ){
80419 rc = SQLITE_NOMEM;
80420 }
80421
80422 /* Lock the destination database, if it is not locked already. */
80423 if( SQLITE_OK==rc && p->bDestLocked==0
80424 && SQLITE_OK==(rc = sqlite3BtreeBeginTrans(p->pDest, 2,
80425 (int*)&p->iDestSchema))
80426 ){
80427 p->bDestLocked = 1;
80428 }
80429
80430 /* Do not allow backup if the destination database is in WAL mode
80431 ** and the page sizes are different between source and destination */
80432 pgszSrc = sqlite3BtreeGetPageSize(p->pSrc);
80433 pgszDest = sqlite3BtreeGetPageSize(p->pDest);
80434 destMode = sqlite3PagerGetJournalMode(sqlite3BtreePager(p->pDest));
80435 if( SQLITE_OK==rc
80436 && (destMode==PAGER_JOURNALMODE_WAL || sqlite3PagerIsMemdb(pDestPager))
80437 && pgszSrc!=pgszDest
80438 ){
80439 rc = SQLITE_READONLY;
80440 }
80441
80442 /* Now that there is a read-lock on the source database, query the
80443 ** source pager for the number of pages in the database.
80444 */
80445 nSrcPage = (int)sqlite3BtreeLastPage(p->pSrc);
80446 assert( nSrcPage>=0 );
80447 for(ii=0; (nPage<0 || ii<nPage) && p->iNext<=(Pgno)nSrcPage && !rc; ii++){
80448 const Pgno iSrcPg = p->iNext; /* Source page number */
80449 if( iSrcPg!=PENDING_BYTE_PAGE(p->pSrc->pBt) ){
80450 DbPage *pSrcPg; /* Source page object */
80451 rc = sqlite3PagerGet(pSrcPager, iSrcPg, &pSrcPg,PAGER_GET_READONLY);
80452 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){
80453 rc = backupOnePage(p, iSrcPg, sqlite3PagerGetData(pSrcPg), 0);
80454 sqlite3PagerUnref(pSrcPg);
80455 }
80456 }
80457 p->iNext++;
80458 }
80459 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){
80460 p->nPagecount = nSrcPage;
80461 p->nRemaining = nSrcPage+1-p->iNext;
80462 if( p->iNext>(Pgno)nSrcPage ){
80463 rc = SQLITE_DONE;
80464 }else if( !p->isAttached ){
80465 attachBackupObject(p);
80466 }
80467 }
80468
80469 /* Update the schema version field in the destination database. This
80470 ** is to make sure that the schema-version really does change in
80471 ** the case where the source and destination databases have the
80472 ** same schema version.
80473 */

80478 }
80479 if( rc==SQLITE_OK || rc==SQLITE_DONE ){

80481 }

80487 rc = sqlite3BtreeSetVersion(p->pDest, 2);
80488 }
80489 }
80490 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){

80492 /* Set nDestTruncate to the final number of pages in the destination
80493 ** database. The complication here is that the destination page
80494 ** size may be different to the source page size.
80495 **
80496 ** If the source page size is smaller than the destination page size,
80497 ** round up. In this case the call to sqlite3OsTruncate() below will
80498 ** fix the size of the file. However it is important to call
80499 ** sqlite3PagerTruncateImage() here so that any pages in the
80500 ** destination file that lie beyond the nDestTruncate page mark are
80501 ** journalled by PagerCommitPhaseOne() before they are destroyed
80502 ** by the file truncation.
80503 */
80504 assert( pgszSrc==sqlite3BtreeGetPageSize(p->pSrc) );
80505 assert( pgszDest==sqlite3BtreeGetPageSize(p->pDest) );
80506 if( pgszSrc<pgszDest ){
80507 int ratio = pgszDest/pgszSrc;
80508 nDestTruncate = (nSrcPage+ratio-1)/ratio;
80509 if( nDestTruncate==(int)PENDING_BYTE_PAGE(p->pDest->pBt) ){
80510 nDestTruncate--;
80511 }
80512 }else{
80513 nDestTruncate = nSrcPage * (pgszSrc/pgszDest);
80514 }
80515 assert( nDestTruncate>0 );
80516
80517 if( pgszSrc<pgszDest ){
80518 /* If the source page-size is smaller than the destination page-size,
80519 ** two extra things may need to happen:
80520 **
80521 ** * The destination may need to be truncated, and
80522 **
80523 ** * Data stored on the pages immediately following the
80524 ** pending-byte page in the source database may need to be
80525 ** copied into the destination database.
80526 */
80527 const i64 iSize = (i64)pgszSrc * (i64)nSrcPage;
80528 sqlite3_file * const pFile = sqlite3PagerFile(pDestPager);
80529 Pgno iPg;
80530 int nDstPage;
80531 i64 iOff;
80532 i64 iEnd;
80533
80534 assert( pFile );
80535 assert( nDestTruncate==0
80536 || (i64)nDestTruncate*(i64)pgszDest >= iSize || (
80537 nDestTruncate==(int)(PENDING_BYTE_PAGE(p->pDest->pBt)-1)
80538 && iSize>=PENDING_BYTE && iSize<=PENDING_BYTE+pgszDest
80539 ));
80540
80541 /* This block ensures that all data required to recreate the original
80542 ** database has been stored in the journal for pDestPager and the
80543 ** journal synced to disk. So at this point we may safely modify
80544 ** the database file in any way, knowing that if a power failure
80545 ** occurs, the original database will be reconstructed from the
80546 ** journal file. */
80547 sqlite3PagerPagecount(pDestPager, &nDstPage);
80548 for(iPg=nDestTruncate; rc==SQLITE_OK && iPg<=(Pgno)nDstPage; iPg++){
80549 if( iPg!=PENDING_BYTE_PAGE(p->pDest->pBt) ){
80550 DbPage *pPg;
80551 rc = sqlite3PagerGet(pDestPager, iPg, &pPg, 0);
80552 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){
80553 rc = sqlite3PagerWrite(pPg);
80554 sqlite3PagerUnref(pPg);
80555 }
80556 }
80557 }
80558 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){
80559 rc = sqlite3PagerCommitPhaseOne(pDestPager, 0, 1);
80560 }
80561
80562 /* Write the extra pages and truncate the database file as required */
80563 iEnd = MIN(PENDING_BYTE + pgszDest, iSize);
80564 for(
80565 iOff=PENDING_BYTE+pgszSrc;
80566 rc==SQLITE_OK && iOff<iEnd;
80567 iOff+=pgszSrc
80568 ){
80569 PgHdr *pSrcPg = 0;
80570 const Pgno iSrcPg = (Pgno)((iOff/pgszSrc)+1);
80571 rc = sqlite3PagerGet(pSrcPager, iSrcPg, &pSrcPg, 0);
80572 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){
80573 u8 *zData = sqlite3PagerGetData(pSrcPg);
80574 rc = sqlite3OsWrite(pFile, zData, pgszSrc, iOff);
80575 }
80576 sqlite3PagerUnref(pSrcPg);
80577 }
80578 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){
80579 rc = backupTruncateFile(pFile, iSize);
80580 }
80581
80582 /* Sync the database file to disk. */
80583 if( rc==SQLITE_OK ){
80584 rc = sqlite3PagerSync(pDestPager, 0);
80585 }
80586 }else{
80587 sqlite3PagerTruncateImage(pDestPager, nDestTruncate);
80588 rc = sqlite3PagerCommitPhaseOne(pDestPager, 0, 0);
80589 }
80590
80591 /* Finish committing the transaction to the destination database. */
80592 if( SQLITE_OK==rc
80593 && SQLITE_OK==(rc = sqlite3BtreeCommitPhaseTwo(p->pDest, 0))
80594 ){
80595 rc = SQLITE_DONE;
80596 }
80597 }
80598 }

80601 ** on the source database. Close the read transaction here. There is
80602 ** no need to check the return values of the btree methods here, as
80603 ** "committing" a read-only transaction cannot fail.

80605 if( bCloseTrans ){

80607 TESTONLY( rc2 = ) sqlite3BtreeCommitPhaseOne(p->pSrc, 0);
80608 TESTONLY( rc2 |= ) sqlite3BtreeCommitPhaseTwo(p->pSrc, 0);
80609 assert( rc2==SQLITE_OK );
80610 }
80611
80612 if( rc==SQLITE_IOERR_NOMEM ){
80613 rc = SQLITE_NOMEM_BKPT;
80614 }
80615 p->rc = rc;
80616 }

99798#ifdef SQLITE_ENABLE_API_ARMOR

99800 return SQLITE_MISUSE_BKPT;
99801 }
99802#endif

99806
99807 pBlob = (Incrblob *)sqlite3DbMallocZero(db, sizeof(Incrblob));
99808 while(1){
99809 sqlite3ParseObjectInit(&sParse,db);
99810 if( !pBlob ) goto blob_open_out;
99811 sqlite3DbFree(db, zErr);
99812 zErr = 0;
99813
99814 sqlite3BtreeEnterAll(db);
99815 pTab = sqlite3LocateTable(&sParse, 0, zTable, zDb);
99816 if( pTab && IsVirtual(pTab) ){
99817 pTab = 0;
99818 sqlite3ErrorMsg(&sParse, "cannot open virtual table: %s", zTable);
99819 }
99820 if( pTab && !HasRowid(pTab) ){
99821 pTab = 0;
99822 sqlite3ErrorMsg(&sParse, "cannot open table without rowid: %s", zTable);
99823 }
99824#ifndef SQLITE_OMIT_VIEW
99825 if( pTab && IsView(pTab) ){
99826 pTab = 0;
99827 sqlite3ErrorMsg(&sParse, "cannot open view: %s", zTable);
99828 }
99829#endif
99830 if( !pTab ){
99831 if( sParse.zErrMsg ){
99832 sqlite3DbFree(db, zErr);
99833 zErr = sParse.zErrMsg;
99834 sParse.zErrMsg = 0;
99835 }
99836 rc = SQLITE_ERROR;
99837 sqlite3BtreeLeaveAll(db);
99838 goto blob_open_out;
99839 }
99840 pBlob->pTab = pTab;
99841 pBlob->zDb = db->aDb[sqlite3SchemaToIndex(db, pTab->pSchema)].zDbSName;
99842
99843 /* Now search pTab for the exact column. */
99844 for(iCol=0; iCol<pTab->nCol; iCol++) {
99845 if( sqlite3StrICmp(pTab->aCol[iCol].zCnName, zColumn)==0 ){
99846 break;
99847 }
99848 }
99849 if( iCol==pTab->nCol ){
99850 sqlite3DbFree(db, zErr);
99851 zErr = sqlite3MPrintf(db, "no such column: \"%s\"", zColumn);
99852 rc = SQLITE_ERROR;
99853 sqlite3BtreeLeaveAll(db);
99854 goto blob_open_out;
99855 }
99856
99857 /* If the value is being opened for writing, check that the
99858 ** column is not indexed, and that it is not part of a foreign key.
99859 */
99860 if( wrFlag ){
99861 const char *zFault = 0;
99862 Index *pIdx;
99863#ifndef SQLITE_OMIT_FOREIGN_KEY
99864 if( db->flags&SQLITE_ForeignKeys ){
99865 /* Check that the column is not part of an FK child key definition. It
99866 ** is not necessary to check if it is part of a parent key, as parent
99867 ** key columns must be indexed. The check below will pick up this
99868 ** case. */
99869 FKey *pFKey;
99870 assert( IsOrdinaryTable(pTab) );
99871 for(pFKey=pTab->u.tab.pFKey; pFKey; pFKey=pFKey->pNextFrom){
99872 int j;
99873 for(j=0; j<pFKey->nCol; j++){
99874 if( pFKey->aCol[j].iFrom==iCol ){
99875 zFault = "foreign key";
99876 }
99877 }
99878 }
99879 }
99880#endif
99881 for(pIdx=pTab->pIndex; pIdx; pIdx=pIdx->pNext){
99882 int j;
99883 for(j=0; j<pIdx->nKeyCol; j++){
99884 /* FIXME: Be smarter about indexes that use expressions */
99885 if( pIdx->aiColumn[j]==iCol || pIdx->aiColumn[j]==XN_EXPR ){
99886 zFault = "indexed";
99887 }
99888 }
99889 }
99890 if( zFault ){
99891 sqlite3DbFree(db, zErr);
99892 zErr = sqlite3MPrintf(db, "cannot open %s column for writing", zFault);
99893 rc = SQLITE_ERROR;
99894 sqlite3BtreeLeaveAll(db);
99895 goto blob_open_out;
99896 }
99897 }

99900 assert( pBlob->pStmt || db->mallocFailed );
99901 if( pBlob->pStmt ){
99902
99903 /* This VDBE program seeks a btree cursor to the identified
99904 ** db/table/row entry. The reason for using a vdbe program instead
99905 ** of writing code to use the b-tree layer directly is that the
99906 ** vdbe program will take advantage of the various transaction,
99907 ** locking and error handling infrastructure built into the vdbe.
99908 **
99909 ** After seeking the cursor, the vdbe executes an OP_ResultRow.
99910 ** Code external to the Vdbe then "borrows" the b-tree cursor and
99911 ** uses it to implement the blob_read(), blob_write() and
99912 ** blob_bytes() functions.
99913 **
99914 ** The sqlite3_blob_close() function finalizes the vdbe program,
99915 ** which closes the b-tree cursor and (possibly) commits the
99916 ** transaction.
99917 */
99918 static const int iLn = VDBE_OFFSET_LINENO(2);
99919 static const VdbeOpList openBlob[] = {
99920 {OP_TableLock, 0, 0, 0}, /* 0: Acquire a read or write lock */
99921 {OP_OpenRead, 0, 0, 0}, /* 1: Open a cursor */
99922 /* blobSeekToRow() will initialize r[1] to the desired rowid */
99923 {OP_NotExists, 0, 5, 1}, /* 2: Seek the cursor to rowid=r[1] */
99924 {OP_Column, 0, 0, 1}, /* 3 */
99925 {OP_ResultRow, 1, 0, 0}, /* 4 */
99926 {OP_Halt, 0, 0, 0}, /* 5 */
99927 };
99928 Vdbe *v = (Vdbe *)pBlob->pStmt;
99929 int iDb = sqlite3SchemaToIndex(db, pTab->pSchema);
99930 VdbeOp *aOp;
99931
99932 sqlite3VdbeAddOp4Int(v, OP_Transaction, iDb, wrFlag,
99933 pTab->pSchema->schema_cookie,
99934 pTab->pSchema->iGeneration);
99935 sqlite3VdbeChangeP5(v, 1);
99936 assert( sqlite3VdbeCurrentAddr(v)==2 || db->mallocFailed );
99937 aOp = sqlite3VdbeAddOpList(v, ArraySize(openBlob), openBlob, iLn);
99938
99939 /* Make sure a mutex is held on the table to be accessed */
99940 sqlite3VdbeUsesBtree(v, iDb);
99941
99942 if( db->mallocFailed==0 ){
99943 assert( aOp!=0 );
99944 /* Configure the OP_TableLock instruction */
99945#ifdef SQLITE_OMIT_SHARED_CACHE
99946 aOp[0].opcode = OP_Noop;
99947#else
99948 aOp[0].p1 = iDb;
99949 aOp[0].p2 = pTab->tnum;
99950 aOp[0].p3 = wrFlag;
99951 sqlite3VdbeChangeP4(v, 2, pTab->zName, P4_TRANSIENT);
99952 }
99953 if( db->mallocFailed==0 ){
99954#endif
99955
99956 /* Remove either the OP_OpenWrite or OpenRead. Set the P2
99957 ** parameter of the other to pTab->tnum. */
99958 if( wrFlag ) aOp[1].opcode = OP_OpenWrite;
99959 aOp[1].p2 = pTab->tnum;
99960 aOp[1].p3 = iDb;
99961
99962 /* Configure the number of columns. Configure the cursor to
99963 ** think that the table has one more column than it really
99964 ** does. An OP_Column to retrieve this imaginary column will
99965 ** always return an SQL NULL. This is useful because it means
99966 ** we can invoke OP_Column to fill in the vdbe cursors type
99967 ** and offset cache without causing any IO.
99968 */
99969 aOp[1].p4type = P4_INT32;
99970 aOp[1].p4.i = pTab->nCol+1;
99971 aOp[3].p2 = pTab->nCol;
99972

45183 {
45184 /*
45185 ** The following macro defines an initializer for an sqlite3_vfs object.
45186 ** The name of the VFS is NAME. The pAppData is a pointer to a pointer
45187 ** to the "finder" function. (pAppData is a pointer to a pointer because
45188 ** silly C90 rules prohibit a void* from being cast to a function pointer
45189 ** and so we have to go through the intermediate pointer to avoid problems
45190 ** when compiling with -pedantic-errors on GCC.)
45191 **
45192 ** The FINDER parameter to this macro is the name of the pointer to the
45193 ** finder-function. The finder-function returns a pointer to the
45194 ** sqlite_io_methods object that implements the desired locking
45195 ** behaviors. See the division above that contains the IOMETHODS
45196 ** macro for addition information on finder-functions.
45197 **
45198 ** Most finders simply return a pointer to a fixed sqlite3_io_methods
45199 ** object. But the "autolockIoFinder" available on MacOSX does a little
45200 ** more than that; it looks at the filesystem type that hosts the
45201 ** database file and tries to choose an locking method appropriate for
45202 ** that filesystem time.
45203 */
45204 #define UNIXVFS(VFSNAME, FINDER) { \
45205 3, /* iVersion */ \
45206 sizeof(unixFile), /* szOsFile */ \
45207 MAX_PATHNAME, /* mxPathname */ \
45208 0, /* pNext */ \
45209 VFSNAME, /* zName */ \
45210 (void*)&FINDER, /* pAppData */ \
45211 unixOpen, /* xOpen */ \
45212 unixDelete, /* xDelete */ \
45213 unixAccess, /* xAccess */ \
45214 unixFullPathname, /* xFullPathname */ \
45215 unixDlOpen, /* xDlOpen */ \
45216 unixDlError, /* xDlError */ \
45217 unixDlSym, /* xDlSym */ \
45218 unixDlClose, /* xDlClose */ \
45219 unixRandomness, /* xRandomness */ \
45220 unixSleep, /* xSleep */ \
45221 unixCurrentTime, /* xCurrentTime */ \
45222 unixGetLastError, /* xGetLastError */ \
45223 unixCurrentTimeInt64, /* xCurrentTimeInt64 */ \

30882 buf[length++] = *(bufpt++);
30883 }
30884 }
30885 }else{
30886 buf[0] = 0;
30887 }
30888 }else{
30889 unsigned int ch = va_arg(ap,unsigned int);
30890 if( ch<0x00080 ){
30891 buf[0] = ch & 0xff;
30892 length = 1;
30893 }else if( ch<0x00800 ){
30894 buf[0] = 0xc0 + (u8)((ch>>6)&0x1f);
30895 buf[1] = 0x80 + (u8)(ch & 0x3f);
30896 length = 2;
30897 }else if( ch<0x10000 ){
30898 buf[0] = 0xe0 + (u8)((ch>>12)&0x0f);
30899 buf[1] = 0x80 + (u8)((ch>>6) & 0x3f);
30900 buf[2] = 0x80 + (u8)(ch & 0x3f);
30901 length = 3;
30902 }else{
30903 buf[0] = 0xf0 + (u8)((ch>>18) & 0x07);
30904 buf[1] = 0x80 + (u8)((ch>>12) & 0x3f);
30905 buf[2] = 0x80 + (u8)((ch>>6) & 0x3f);
30906 buf[3] = 0x80 + (u8)(ch & 0x3f);
30907 length = 4;
30908 }
30909 }
30910 if( precision>1 ){
30911 i64 nPrior = 1;
30912 width -= precision-1;
30913 if( width>1 && !flag_leftjustify ){
30914 sqlite3_str_appendchar(pAccum, width-1, ' ');
30915 width = 0;
30916 }
30917 sqlite3_str_append(pAccum, buf, length);
30918 precision--;
30919 while( precision > 1 ){
30920 i64 nCopyBytes;
30921 if( nPrior > precision-1 ) nPrior = precision - 1;
30922 nCopyBytes = length*nPrior;
30923 if( nCopyBytes + pAccum->nChar >= pAccum->nAlloc ){
30924 sqlite3StrAccumEnlarge(pAccum, nCopyBytes);
30925 }
30926 if( pAccum->accError ) break;
30927 sqlite3_str_append(pAccum,
30928 &pAccum->zText[pAccum->nChar-nCopyBytes], nCopyBytes);
30929 precision -= nPrior;
30930 nPrior *= 2;
30931 }
30932 }
30933 bufpt = buf;
30934 flag_altform2 = 1;
30935 goto adjust_width_for_utf8;
30936 case etSTRING:
30937 case etDYNSTRING:
30938 if( bArgList ){
30939 bufpt = getTextArg(pArgList);
30940 xtype = etSTRING;
30941 }else{
30942 bufpt = va_arg(ap,char*);
30943 }
30944 if( bufpt==0 ){
30945 bufpt = "";
30946 }else if( xtype==etDYNSTRING ){
30947 if( pAccum->nChar==0
30948 && pAccum->mxAlloc
30949 && width==0
30950 && precision<0
30951 && pAccum->accError==0
30952 ){
30953 /* Special optimization for sqlite3_mprintf("%z..."):
30954 ** Extend an existing memory allocation rather than creating
30955 ** a new one. */
30956 assert( (pAccum->printfFlags&SQLITE_PRINTF_MALLOCED)==0 );
30957 pAccum->zText = bufpt;
30958 pAccum->nAlloc = sqlite3DbMallocSize(pAccum->db, bufpt);
30959 pAccum->nChar = 0x7fffffff & (int)strlen(bufpt);
30960 pAccum->printfFlags |= SQLITE_PRINTF_MALLOCED;
30961 length = 0;
30962 break;
30963 }
30964 zExtra = bufpt;
30965 }
30966 if( precision>=0 ){
30967 if( flag_altform2 ){
30968 /* Set length to the number of bytes needed in order to display
30969 ** precision characters */
30970 unsigned char *z = (unsigned char*)bufpt;
30971 while( precision-- > 0 && z[0] ){
30972 SQLITE_SKIP_UTF8(z);
30973 }
30974 length = (int)(z - (unsigned char*)bufpt);
30975 }else{
30976 for(length=0; length<precision && bufpt[length]; length++){}
30977 }
30978 }else{
30979 length = 0x7fffffff & (int)strlen(bufpt);
30980 }
30981 adjust_width_for_utf8:
30982 if( flag_altform2 && width>0 ){
30983 /* Adjust width to account for extra bytes in UTF-8 characters */
30984 int ii = length - 1;
30985 while( ii>=0 ) if( (bufpt[ii--] & 0xc0)==0x80 ) width++;
30986 }
30987 break;
30988 case etSQLESCAPE: /* %q: Escape ' characters */
30989 case etSQLESCAPE2: /* %Q: Escape ' and enclose in '...' */
30990 case etSQLESCAPE3: { /* %w: Escape " characters */
30991 i64 i, j, k, n;
30992 int needQuote, isnull;
30993 char ch;
30994 char q = ((xtype==etSQLESCAPE3)?'"':'\''); /* Quote character */
30995 char *escarg;
30996
30997 if( bArgList ){
30998 escarg = getTextArg(pArgList);
30999 }else{
31000 escarg = va_arg(ap,char*);
31001 }
31002 isnull = escarg==0;
31003 if( isnull ) escarg = (xtype==etSQLESCAPE2 ? "NULL" : "(NULL)");
31004 /* For %q, %Q, and %w, the precision is the number of bytes (or
31005 ** characters if the ! flags is present) to use from the input.
31006 ** Because of the extra quoting characters inserted, the number
31007 ** of output characters may be larger than the precision.
31008 */
31009 k = precision;
31010 for(i=n=0; k!=0 && (ch=escarg[i])!=0; i++, k--){
31011 if( ch==q ) n++;
31012 if( flag_altform2 && (ch&0xc0)==0xc0 ){
31013 while( (escarg[i+1]&0xc0)==0x80 ){ i++; }
31014 }
31015 }
31016 needQuote = !isnull && xtype==etSQLESCAPE2;
31017 n += i + 3;
31018 if( n>etBUFSIZE ){
31019 bufpt = zExtra = printfTempBuf(pAccum, n);
31020 if( bufpt==0 ) return;
31021 }else{
31022 bufpt = buf;
31023 }
31024 j = 0;
31025 if( needQuote ) bufpt[j++] = q;
31026 k = i;
31027 for(i=0; i<k; i++){
31028 bufpt[j++] = ch = escarg[i];
31029 if( ch==q ) bufpt[j++] = ch;
31030 }
31031 if( needQuote ) bufpt[j++] = q;
31032 bufpt[j] = 0;
31033 length = j;
31034 goto adjust_width_for_utf8;
31035 }
31036 case etTOKEN: {
31037 if( (pAccum->printfFlags & SQLITE_PRINTF_INTERNAL)==0 ) return;
31038 if( flag_alternateform ){
31039 /* %#T means an Expr pointer that uses Expr.u.zToken */
31040 Expr *pExpr = va_arg(ap,Expr*);
31041 if( ALWAYS(pExpr) && ALWAYS(!ExprHasProperty(pExpr,EP_IntValue)) ){
31042 sqlite3_str_appendall(pAccum, (const char*)pExpr->u.zToken);
31043 sqlite3RecordErrorOffsetOfExpr(pAccum->db, pExpr);
31044 }
31045 }else{
31046 /* %T means a Token pointer */
31047 Token *pToken = va_arg(ap, Token*);
31048 assert( bArgList==0 );
31049 if( pToken && pToken->n ){
31050 sqlite3_str_append(pAccum, (const char*)pToken->z, pToken->n);
31051 sqlite3RecordErrorByteOffset(pAccum->db, pToken->z);
31052 }
31053 }
31054 length = width = 0;
31055 break;
31056 }
31057 case etSRCITEM: {
31058 SrcItem *pItem;
31059 if( (pAccum->printfFlags & SQLITE_PRINTF_INTERNAL)==0 ) return;
31060 pItem = va_arg(ap, SrcItem*);
31061 assert( bArgList==0 );
31062 if( pItem->zAlias && !flag_altform2 ){
31063 sqlite3_str_appendall(pAccum, pItem->zAlias);
31064 }else if( pItem->zName ){
31065 if( pItem->zDatabase ){
31066 sqlite3_str_appendall(pAccum, pItem->zDatabase);
31067 sqlite3_str_append(pAccum, ".", 1);
31068 }
31069 sqlite3_str_appendall(pAccum, pItem->zName);
31070 }else if( pItem->zAlias ){
31071 sqlite3_str_appendall(pAccum, pItem->zAlias);
31072 }else{
31073 Select *pSel = pItem->pSelect;
31074 assert( pSel!=0 );
31075 if( pSel->selFlags & SF_NestedFrom ){
31076 sqlite3_str_appendf(pAccum, "(join-%u)", pSel->selId);
31077 }else{
31078 sqlite3_str_appendf(pAccum, "(subquery-%u)", pSel->selId);
31079 }
31080 }
31081 length = width = 0;
31082 break;
31083 }
31084 default: {
31085 assert( xtype==etINVALID );
31086 return;
31087 }
31088 }/* End switch over the format type */
31089 /*
31090 ** The text of the conversion is pointed to by "bufpt" and is
31091 ** "length" characters long. The field width is "width". Do
31092 ** the output. Both length and width are in bytes, not characters,
31093 ** at this point. If the "!" flag was present on string conversions
31094 ** indicating that width and precision should be expressed in characters,
31095 ** then the values have been translated prior to reaching this point.
31096 */
31097 width -= length;
31098 if( width>0 ){
31099 if( !flag_leftjustify ) sqlite3_str_appendchar(pAccum, width, ' ');
31100 sqlite3_str_append(pAccum, bufpt, length);
31101 if( flag_leftjustify ) sqlite3_str_appendchar(pAccum, width, ' ');
31102 }else{
31103 sqlite3_str_append(pAccum, bufpt, length);
31104 }

178935 ** the PRNG seed.
178936 **
178937 ** x!=0 && db==0 Seed the PRNG to the value of x.
178938 **
178939 ** x==0 && db==0 Revert to default behavior of using the
178940 ** xRandomness method on the primary VFS.
178941 **
178942 ** This test-control also resets the PRNG so that the new seed will
178943 ** be used for the next call to sqlite3_randomness().
178944 */
178945#ifndef SQLITE_OMIT_WSD
178946 case SQLITE_TESTCTRL_PRNG_SEED: {
178947 int x = va_arg(ap, int);
178948 int y;
178949 sqlite3 *db = va_arg(ap, sqlite3*);
178950 assert( db==0 || db->aDb[0].pSchema!=0 );
178951 if( db && (y = db->aDb[0].pSchema->schema_cookie)!=0 ){ x = y; }
178952 sqlite3Config.iPrngSeed = x;
178953 sqlite3_randomness(0,0);
178954 break;
178955 }
178956#endif

178973 /*
178974 ** sqlite3_test_control(FAULT_INSTALL, xCallback)
178975 **
178976 ** Arrange to invoke xCallback() whenever sqlite3FaultSim() is called,
178977 ** if xCallback is not NULL.
178978 **
178979 ** As a test of the fault simulator mechanism itself, sqlite3FaultSim(0)
178980 ** is called immediately after installing the new callback and the return
178981 ** value from sqlite3FaultSim(0) becomes the return from
178982 ** sqlite3_test_control().
178983 */
178984 case SQLITE_TESTCTRL_FAULT_INSTALL: {
178985 /* A bug in MSVC prevents it from understanding pointers to functions
178986 ** types in the second argument to va_arg(). Work around the problem
178987 ** using a typedef.
178988 ** http://support.microsoft.com/kb/47961 <-- dead hyperlink
178989 ** Search at http://web.archive.org/ to find the 2015-03-16 archive
178990 ** of the link above to see the original text.
178991 ** sqlite3GlobalConfig.xTestCallback = va_arg(ap, int(*)(int));
178992 */
178993 typedef int(*sqlite3FaultFuncType)(int);
178994 sqlite3GlobalConfig.xTestCallback = va_arg(ap, sqlite3FaultFuncType);
178995 rc = sqlite3FaultSim(0);
178996 break;
178997 }

179017 **
179018 ** Set the PENDING byte to the value in the argument, if X>0.
179019 ** Make no changes if X==0. Return the value of the pending byte
179020 ** as it existing before this routine was called.
179021 **
179022 ** IMPORTANT: Changing the PENDING byte from 0x40000000 results in
179023 ** an incompatible database file format. Changing the PENDING byte

179027 case SQLITE_TESTCTRL_PENDING_BYTE: {

179029#ifndef SQLITE_OMIT_WSD
179030 {
179031 unsigned int newVal = va_arg(ap, unsigned int);
179032 if( newVal ) sqlite3PendingByte = newVal;
179033 }
179034#endif
179035 break;
179036 }

179038 /*
179039 ** sqlite3_test_control(SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ASSERT, int X)
179040 **
179041 ** This action provides a run-time test to see whether or not
179042 ** assert() was enabled at compile-time. If X is true and assert()
179043 ** is enabled, then the return value is true. If X is true and
179044 ** assert() is disabled, then the return value is zero. If X is
179045 ** false and assert() is enabled, then the assertion fires and the
179046 ** process aborts. If X is false and assert() is disabled, then the
179047 ** return value is zero.
179048 */
179049 case SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ASSERT: {
179050 volatile int x = 0;
179051 assert( /*side-effects-ok*/ (x = va_arg(ap,int))!=0 );
179052 rc = x;
179053#if defined(SQLITE_DEBUG)
179054 /* Invoke these debugging routines so that the compiler does not
179055 ** issue "defined but not used" warnings. */
179056 if( x==9999 ){
179057 sqlite3ShowExpr(0);
179058 sqlite3ShowExpr(0);
179059 sqlite3ShowExprList(0);
179060 sqlite3ShowIdList(0);
179061 sqlite3ShowSrcList(0);
179062 sqlite3ShowWith(0);
179063 sqlite3ShowUpsert(0);
179064 sqlite3ShowTriggerStep(0);
179065 sqlite3ShowTriggerStepList(0);
179066 sqlite3ShowTrigger(0);
179067 sqlite3ShowTriggerList(0);
179068#ifndef SQLITE_OMIT_WINDOWFUNC
179069 sqlite3ShowWindow(0);
179070 sqlite3ShowWinFunc(0);
179071#endif
179072 sqlite3ShowSelect(0);
179073 }
179074#endif
179075 break;
179076 }

179078
179079 /*
179080 ** sqlite3_test_control(SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ALWAYS, int X)
179081 **
179082 ** This action provides a run-time test to see how the ALWAYS and
179083 ** NEVER macros were defined at compile-time.
179084 **
179085 ** The return value is ALWAYS(X) if X is true, or 0 if X is false.
179086 **
179087 ** The recommended test is X==2. If the return value is 2, that means
179088 ** ALWAYS() and NEVER() are both no-op pass-through macros, which is the
179089 ** default setting. If the return value is 1, then ALWAYS() is either
179090 ** hard-coded to true or else it asserts if its argument is false.
179091 ** The first behavior (hard-coded to true) is the case if
179092 ** SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ASSERT shows that assert() is disabled and the second
179093 ** behavior (assert if the argument to ALWAYS() is false) is the case if
179094 ** SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ASSERT shows that assert() is enabled.
179095 **
179096 ** The run-time test procedure might look something like this:
179097 **
179098 ** if( sqlite3_test_control(SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ALWAYS, 2)==2 ){
179099 ** // ALWAYS() and NEVER() are no-op pass-through macros
179100 ** }else if( sqlite3_test_control(SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ASSERT, 1) ){
179101 ** // ALWAYS(x) asserts that x is true. NEVER(x) asserts x is false.
179102 ** }else{
179103 ** // ALWAYS(x) is a constant 1. NEVER(x) is a constant 0.
179104 ** }
179105 */
179106 case SQLITE_TESTCTRL_ALWAYS: {
179107 int x = va_arg(ap,int);
179108 rc = x ? ALWAYS(x) : 0;
179109 break;
179110 }
179111
179112 /*
179113 ** sqlite3_test_control(SQLITE_TESTCTRL_BYTEORDER);
179114 **
179115 ** The integer returned reveals the byte-order of the computer on which
179116 ** SQLite is running:
179117 **
179118 ** 1 big-endian, determined at run-time
179119 ** 10 little-endian, determined at run-time
179120 ** 432101 big-endian, determined at compile-time
179121 ** 123410 little-endian, determined at compile-time
179122 */
179123 case SQLITE_TESTCTRL_BYTEORDER: {
179124 rc = SQLITE_BYTEORDER*100 + SQLITE_LITTLEENDIAN*10 + SQLITE_BIGENDIAN;
179125 break;
179126 }

179147 ** processing.

179161 }else{
179162 sqlite3GlobalConfig.xAltLocaltime = 0;
179163 }
179164 break;

179250 /* sqlite3_test_control(SQLITE_TESTCTRL_IMPOSTER, db, dbName, onOff, tnum);
179251 **
179252 ** This test control is used to create imposter tables. "db" is a pointer
179253 ** to the database connection. dbName is the database name (ex: "main" or
179254 ** "temp") which will receive the imposter. "onOff" turns imposter mode on
179255 ** or off. "tnum" is the root page of the b-tree to which the imposter
179256 ** table should connect.
179257 **
179258 ** Enable imposter mode only when the schema has already been parsed. Then
179259 ** run a single CREATE TABLE statement to construct the imposter table in
179260 ** the parsed schema. Then turn imposter mode back off again.
179261 **
179262 ** If onOff==0 and tnum>0 then reset the schema for all databases, causing
179263 ** the schema to be reparsed the next time it is needed. This has the
179264 ** effect of erasing all imposter tables.
179265 */
179266 case SQLITE_TESTCTRL_IMPOSTER: {
179267 sqlite3 *db = va_arg(ap, sqlite3*);
179268 int iDb;
179269 sqlite3_mutex_enter(db->mutex);
179270 iDb = sqlite3FindDbName(db, va_arg(ap,const char*));
179271 if( iDb>=0 ){
179272 db->init.iDb = iDb;
179273 db->init.busy = db->init.imposterTable = va_arg(ap,int);
179274 db->init.newTnum = va_arg(ap,int);
179275 if( db->init.busy==0 && db->init.newTnum>0 ){
179276 sqlite3ResetAllSchemasOfConnection(db);
179277 }
179278 }
179279 sqlite3_mutex_leave(db->mutex);
179280 break;
179281 }
